element.name: Walking the Walk by Windsockers, Multi-cache (2/2)

long-description.p: Portrane is a small seaside village in North County Dublin. The name Portrane comes from Portrachrainn, or the port of the Rechru. Rechru was the pre Norse name for Lambay Island, meaning Lamb Island, so called by the Danes because of the sheep grazing there.

Burrow Beach is a long, sandy beach that extends from the village of Portrane northward into Rogerstown Estuary. The area supports a diverse range of native species and is known for certain birds and plants in particular.
To find the cache you will need to take a walk along the Brook Beach and also the sand ladder pathway.
But first you need to visit the information sign for “The Brook Beach” at the above coordinates and find the dates for the following.

Note the year the "Brook" was first constructed call this ABCD.
Note the last to digits after Bishop Comyn Call this EF
At this location find the five digit number call this GHIJK
Near this location note the last two digits of the ID number mentioned call this LM
The cache can be found at N53 30.M(E-M)(L+M) W 6 0G.J(M+L)I
Please rehide the cache carefully to prevent muggles from discovering its location.

2010-03-14T19:00:00Z : Found it by orangetigerprawn
Found on a sunny spring afternoon. I hadn't been down this far in years. The last time I was here I think the old tram that had been used as a chalet was still here. An aunt of mine owned it for a period once upon a year. There were quite a number of walkers out and about along the beach but the area around the cache was quiet enough. The cache took a bit of finding and was being guarded by a ferocious slug.
Go raibh maith agat as an taisce.

Beautiful walk along the sea, found easily... In: GC TFTC...[:D]

2010-01-23T20:00:00Z : Found it by Fjon
I've no idea how I missed this yesterday! Found it within seconds this time. I think I was too focused on 7 last time, when it's actually 8!

groundspeak:cache.groundspeak:name: Walking the Walk
groundspeak:cache.groundspeak:long_description:
Portrane is a small seaside village in North County Dublin. The name Portrane comes from Portrachrainn, or the port of the Rechru. Rechru was the pre Norse name for Lambay Island, meaning Lamb Island, so called by the Danes because of the sheep grazing there.

Burrow Beach is a long, sandy beach that extends from the village of Portrane northward into Rogerstown Estuary. The area supports a diverse range of native species and is known for certain birds and plants in particular.

The Cache

To find the cache you will need to take a walk along the Brook Beach and also the sand ladder pathway.

But first you need to visit the information sign for “The Brook Beach” at the above coordinates and find the dates for the following.

Note the year the "Brook" was first constructed call this ABCD.
Note the last to digits after Bishop Comyn Call this EF

Go to N53 30.(B-D)C(C-D) W6 06.E(C-B+A)F

At this location find the five digit number call this GHIJK

Go to N53 30.IDJ W6 0G.(J-A)HF

Near this location note the last two digits of the ID number mentioned call this LM

Final Location

The cache can be found at N53 30.M(E-M)(L+M) W 6 0G.J(M+L)I

Please rehide the cache carefully to prevent muggles from discovering its location.
